text:
so, in early january i started struggling with agoraphobia. it distorts things, to say the least. .
.
i‚Äôm no stranger to panic attacks, but these particular attacks are different - both in how they manifest, and in the impact they have on me. i have moments when i get very discouraged and feel like i‚Äôm just a shell of the person i was a couple of years ago. .
.
but the truth is, that me was in a ton of denial, and was unwittingly playing a role to please and appease some very unhealthy people. i am on a wild ride, for sure, but it‚Äôs an honest ride now. my body consistently revolts each time i own (or need to own) more of my story, and i‚Äôm learning - even when it shows up as agoraphobia - to thank my body for a.) trying so hard (and succeeding) to hold down the fort all these years, and b.) letting me know when there‚Äôs something i need to face, or when we‚Äôve hit the issues jackpot. .
.
our bodies really are a marvel. ‚Äúfearfully and wonderfully made.‚Äù and the more we lean in, and embrace symptoms as information - indicators - the more intelligently and compassionately we can move forward. .
.
no matter what you‚Äôre struggling with today, remember that you are not alone, and that you are healing. you. are. healing.  lean in and keep going. üí™üèº
.
.

text:
does this look like a woman who's got it together? i was in a new baby bubble, not knowing my beloved nan was about to die suddenly or that my employer was going to ghost me and throw me out of my job. this is not a woman who could've jumped into a tribunal claim. i, like many mums, have been denied justice due to an outdated system.
the idea that pregnant women and new mums can start a tribunal process within 3 months is utter insanity and it results in 0.6% of victims raising a claim.  the 3-month time limit on employment tribunals has to be raised. #weneedyou
please tell @beisgovuk now as the more they hear from us the more likely they are to do something about it.
my pal joeli @pregnantthenscrewed has even written the email for you! link in comments below. .
.
.

text:
most of us have things about ourselves &/or past we don‚Äôt like, wish could be erased, or at the very least, covered up.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
but i found (the hard way) that the road to healing comes when we stop running, turn around, & confront the hard truths‚Äî& all the pain that comes with it, face-to-face.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
when i finally stopped running/hiding, i allowed god into the healing process. or maybe it was god who helped me stop running. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
but i allowed god in. and when i did, i discovered he‚Äôd been there all along. i just couldn‚Äôt see him, or afraid of feeling judged, maybe i didn‚Äôt look for him.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
and i remember the words of john, ‚Äújesus wept.‚Äù‚†Ä
‚†Ä
god grieves with those who are hurting. he‚Äôs broken over the suffering more than we are. he doesn‚Äôt like it anymore than we do. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
and that comforts me.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
we don‚Äôt serve a distant god. we serve a god who comes near to the broken-hearted, who grieves with us in our pain. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
yesterday i read story after story of women who have endured sexual abuse at the hands of their pastors. my heart grieves for them & the evil that‚Äôs crept into churches all across our ‚Äúchristian‚Äù country. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
but knowing god is disgusted with it & grieves with them, & stands up for them, gives me hope. i pray that the light that‚Äôs currently being shown into the dark places will bring healing that‚Äôs long overdue.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
#livinghonestly #liveyourtruth #speakyourtruth #innerhealing #soulcare #soulwork #findyourfreedom #graceupongrace #graceandtruth #churchtoo #metoo #houstonchronicle

text:
we are thrilled to share that 20% of donations of $20 or more will go directly to the american civil liberties union (aclu). please make a donation through our indiegogo campaign: 
https://bit.ly/2gmfj5k

house on fire is a play for today, exposing the ways in which white supremacy twists language and narrative to try to justify its actions. yet the play is also contemporary in how it is made: with a diverse cast and production team (majority poc and female actors), a production devised in collaboration from an open performance text by all on the production team. by utilizing this broad set of voices, in such a democratic manner, we hope to subvert the hive mind mentality and inflammatory rhetoric of trumpian america, and expose it for the babble that it is.
name: HOUSE ON FIRE
tweet_full:
we are thrilled to share that 20% of donations of $20 or more will go directly to the american civil liberties union (aclu). please make a donation through our indiegogo campaign: 
https://bit.ly/2gmfj5k

house on fire is a play for today, exposing the ways in which white supremacy twists language and narrative to try to justify its actions. yet the play is also contemporary in how it is made: with a diverse cast and production team (majority poc and female actors), a production devised in collaboration from an open performance text by all on the production team. by utilizing this broad set of voices, in such a democratic manner, we hope to subvert the hive mind mentality and inflammatory rhetoric of trumpian america, and expose it for the babble that it is.

text: "when we are children we grow from being 100% dependent on our caregivers, to moving into social situations where we grow increasingly dependent on the acceptance and approval of our peers. the need for connection doesn‚Äôt abate, but the group or groups that we look to for connection and acceptance shifts. in his book, ‚Äúsocial: why our brains are wired to connect‚Äù dr. matthew leiberman describes the reality that all pain has a corresponding physical sensation that is an evolutionary survival design. it is meant to draw our attention to a danger‚Äîa vulnerability, whether that is an injury that needs our attention, or the physically uncomfortable sensation of thirst or hunger. a lesser acknowledged physical pain is the pain (sensations) we feel in response to social rejection or loss of connection. we use terms like he ‚Äúbroke my heart‚Äù or ‚Äúi feel crushed‚Äù to describe the pain we feel when we are rejected by someone we are attached to. being ‚Äúbroken hearted‚Äù is quite literally feeling the physical sensation of the loss of an important connection, as it is registered by our brains and felt in our bodies. in fact, leiberman goes on to explain the fact that the very regions of our brain that register physical pain and that are targeted by pain relievers such as tylenol or aleve are the very same regions that light up when we experience the loss of connection or a social rejection. in fact, being connected to other human beings is so important to our survival that some studies suggest a correlation between decrease in social connection with an  increase in mortality (mohanty et al., 2016)." chapter 8: there is nothing to fix #community #healing #books #trauma #adversechildhoodexperiences #yoga #mindfulness #womenempowerment #metoo #social #brain #earlychildhood #development

text:
my cousins and i went to a bar and a couple of guys came over and immediately started talking to us. it became clear to me that these men were problematic when i noticed that all they had to say was ‚Äújoking rude.‚Äù for example, my cousin is a stand up comedian, and upon learning this, one of the soft bois kept finding ways to tell her that he bet she sucked and wasn‚Äôt actually funny. he made sure to laugh when he said it though, as if that made it ok. 
i immediately looked him in his drunk eyes and told him what he was saying was not funny and that he had not earned the right to tease any of us as he had just met us and spent no emotional labor getting to know us and our boundaries. i was surprised to see that my cousin herself came to his rescue saying, ‚Äúhe was just joking!‚Äù i repeated myself to her and said, ‚Äúit‚Äôs not funny. he doesn‚Äôt know you. and it‚Äôs not ok.‚Äù i doubt i made an impact on frat star but i really hope i made my cousin think twice about letting men speak to her like that in the future. ***submit your story of courage here: http://illuminatefilmfestival.com/acts-of-courage-form

text:
love hurts. but not like that. üòò
.
until the #metoo movement started, i don‚Äôt know that i fully realized how easy i have had it in life. when i started hearing friends, family, colleagues, and acquaintances all come out and tell their stories of ‚Äòthat time,‚Äô i was stunned. i‚Äôm no dummy, i know this kind of thing happens, but i had no idea how pervasive the issue was (and is). i had no idea that it was happening to person after person that i know. sometimes right in front of my eyes. üòî
.
love takes work. people argue, disagree, fight, and bicker. but true love does not truly hurt. it does not attack, control, manipulate. though i have never fallen prey to any #metoo situations, i have been in some pretty bad relationships. men who sought to control my destiny (good luck). men who cut me off from friends. men who told me i was dumb (no need to study for that exam, let‚Äôs go out). men who used me for money. men who tried to cut me off from my family. men who made me feel unworthy, undeserving, and sad. üôáüèª‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è
.
i am so blessed that i grew a pair of ovaries and left those d-bags. to all the women on this page, especially the young women: you matter. you will be believed when you speak up. you do not have to stay with that jerk because you worry you‚Äôll never find another. if your partner treats you like crap, if they hurt you psychologically, physically, financially, or emotionally...girl, he‚Äôs just not that into you and tell him boy, bye. üôãüèª‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è
.
trust me. you‚Äôre worth it. üòò
.
what‚Äôs been your best lesson in love?
.

mental health conditions
some of the most serious types of mental illness in the us include:
‚óè anxiety (affecting 42 million adults)
‚óè depression (impacting 16 million adults)
‚óè bipolar disorder (with some 6.1 million adult sufferers)
‚óè schizophrenia (affecting 2.4 million adults) ‚óè autism spectrum disorder (asd) (currently affecting about 3 million, including one in 42 boys and one in 189 girls, with roughly 100 new cases diagnosed daily) 
unfortunately, many conditions remain untreated. approximately 50 percent of youths age eight to fifteen, and 60 percent of adults with mental illness, report they didn‚Äôt receive mental health services in the previous year. this may be caused by the social stigma that is sometimes attached to asking for help, to lack of access to mental health services, to lack of insurance, or to any number of other factors. üõëstress‚ö†Ô∏è pressure or tension that results from a demanding situation. stress can be physical, emotional, or a combination of all the above. ‚ñ™Ô∏è‚ñ™Ô∏è‚ñ™Ô∏è‚ñ™Ô∏è‚ñ™Ô∏è

text:
sex offender registry....part 2
as we discussed yesterday, the sex offender registry is a great tool to help identify the sex offenders in your community. however, the registry will only identify convicted offenders! as parents, we have to monitor everyone around us. teachers, pastors, coaches, relatives, family friends, doctors, and neighbors are all capable of sexual abuse and can molest undetected for years. these people aren't going to be on the registry, yet they are just as dangerous as the people who are (maybe even more so). if you limit your concern to just those who are on the registry, you give opportunity and access to many others who count on you to overlook them due to proximity, affiliation, and perceived trustworthiness.the sex offender registry should be just one of many tools and resources in your family's safety plan. #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #rapevictim #victim #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate #volunteer #activist #superbowl

text:
it can feel terrifying to share the dark parts of yourself. but i feel it‚Äôs deeply important to share my story. if it helps even one person i have served my purpose. trigger warning.
<‚Ä¢>
i used to be a very desperate, hopeless and depressed woman. this will come as a surprise to many who know me. i live in a party city and i was a party girl. always up for a laugh, smiling on the outside but screaming on the inside. i learned from an early age how to hide my dark and desperate feelings. i am a survivor of childhood sexual abuse, something i had deeply repressed and wasn‚Äôt even aware of consciously until 5 years ago.
<‚Ä¢>
one way this trauma manifested in my life is addiction. i am an addict. i used anything and anyone i could to numb out, escape myself and reality. alcohol, drugs, abusive relationships, sex, food...shopping. netflix. it took me 8 months of sobriety to finally be able to admit out loud ‚Äúi am an addict.‚Äù i had internalized my trauma. i had bought into the story that i was unworthy of love and unlovable.
<‚Ä¢>
my heart goes out to my younger self and i send her love everyday. i was so lost for so long. but my heart knew what i couldn‚Äôt believe or feel then. that i could heal. that i could learn and remember how to love myself. that journey began with my decision to pursue a career in massage therapy and the healing arts. i was drawn to the very work i needed to heal myself. it‚Äôs a process and healing isn‚Äôt linear. i had many mentors and healers help guide me along the way, but my heart has been true north. my heart is my connection with source. my heart told me i needed to love myself unconditionally, no matter what. this was the first step of my recovery.
<‚Ä¢>
today am more whole and happy than i have been in this lifetime. i have been sober for a year! i am in a loving and committed relationship with my soulmate. i am doing work i love that allows me to use my gifts to help others. i swear, sometimes i feel like freaking snow white running around the forest singing to animals and spreading sunshine. i still have struggles and i still shed layers, i am still healing. but i love myself. <‚Ä¢>
(continued in comments)üëáüèº

tweet_full:
it can feel terrifying to share the dark parts of yourself. but i feel it‚Äôs deeply important to share my story. if it helps even one person i have served my purpose. trigger warning.
<‚Ä¢>
i used to be a very desperate, hopeless and depressed woman. this will come as a surprise to many who know me. i live in a party city and i was a party girl. always up for a laugh, smiling on the outside but screaming on the inside. i learned from an early age how to hide my dark and desperate feelings. i am a survivor of childhood sexual abuse, something i had deeply repressed and wasn‚Äôt even aware of consciously until 5 years ago.
<‚Ä¢>
one way this trauma manifested in my life is addiction. i am an addict. i used anything and anyone i could to numb out, escape myself and reality. alcohol, drugs, abusive relationships, sex, food...shopping. netflix. it took me 8 months of sobriety to finally be able to admit out loud ‚Äúi am an addict.‚Äù i had internalized my trauma. i had bought into the story that i was unworthy of love and unlovable.
<‚Ä¢>
my heart goes out to my younger self and i send her love everyday. i was so lost for so long. but my heart knew what i couldn‚Äôt believe or feel then. that i could heal. that i could learn and remember how to love myself. that journey began with my decision to pursue a career in massage therapy and the healing arts. i was drawn to the very work i needed to heal myself. it‚Äôs a process and healing isn‚Äôt linear. i had many mentors and healers help guide me along the way, but my heart has been true north. my heart is my connection with source. my heart told me i needed to love myself unconditionally, no matter what. this was the first step of my recovery.
<‚Ä¢>
today am more whole and happy than i have been in this lifetime. i have been sober for a year! i am in a loving and committed relationship with my soulmate. i am doing work i love that allows me to use my gifts to help others. i swear, sometimes i feel like freaking snow white running around the forest singing to animals and spreading sunshine. i still have struggles and i still shed layers, i am still healing. but i love myself. <‚Ä¢>

text:
@musawiramotivates suna ha ke aj phir kisi aurat zaat ko hawas ka nishana bna kar aye ho
suna ha ke phir kisi hawa ke beti ke izzat pamal karke aye hn
ay ibn e adam khud ko smjhte kia ho;binte hawa ko ruswa karke sar pa apne imama e izzat saja ke ;apne mardangi par naaz karte ho
uske tootate wajood ko daikh kar tm khauf e khuda se larze ni
uske siskiyan sun kar tm qehre khuda se kanmpe ni
 uske ankho ma ashke shikayat,uske labon pa faryad e madad daikh ke bh tm sakoon ke neend kaise so kaise  gaye?
isliye sakoon ma ho na ke uske ghar wale izaat ke waja se zubaan pa taale laga chuke hein ; par ku bhol rae h roz e mehshar har taale ke chabi hoge,har aah sune jayege , har zulm ke saza hoge.
tme to haiwan bh kehne ke haq ma ni ha ye zubaan kunke tm to ehsaas se mehrom h .
par jante h agar ye aurat bol uthe to ye zameen uske cheekh se laraz uthe ge 
asmaan uske dhar se kanmp uthe ga 
wo tmhe is tarha rol da ge ke tm aurat lafz se he darne lage gn.. .
.

text:
soooo i just wanted to share something because i was thinking about were i was a few months ago..... a year agoüò≠üò≠(praise god i'm not feeling that nomore...... i was delivered by a angel lol)üëºüèæüôèüèæüëèüèæ. ..... i was hurting,  i was sad .... numb trying to fill my empty void with something new because dealing with someone elses life and bullshit is way easier than dealing with your own that was no longer doing the job, the weed was no longer doing the job..... working but not being paid like i deserved because my pee was dirty or because i was overweight was killing my confidence and ability to take care of myself... and trying to take care of someone else just made it harder but in the end being dumpedü§¶üèæ‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è.... it made me angry and bitter...i felt obligated to do things to my body because i felt too big and unattractive,  i started drinking all the time, i was damn near drunk everyday or every other day along with being cross faded because i smoked half a ounce by thursday....shiddd i'm blessed to still be allowed to have a  bank account and own a computer if you wanna keep it a bucküòÇüòÇüòÇ.... i just wanted to do so much destruction....i probably blocked some of my own blessings, instead of getting help i took the road less should travel(don't be like me and wait till you're about to drown to ask for help) ... regardless of what was done towards me, you never let the enemy get the best of you, that's how you lose the game...... but it showed me my strength.... when you let go of negativity, accept your faults and the transgressions towards you by others, gods gift to you is positivite energy, open arms and the opportunity to start over the right way!!!

text:
rp @jessyforthevoiceless why the dairy industry is cruel on every level.üëáüèº
‚Ä¢ 
when a mother cow gives birth, her calf will be removed within 36 hours, so the farmers can steal and sell the milk that is meant for her baby. (organic-, free range-, pasture raised- farm or not.)
‚Ä¢ 
cows are pregnant for 9 months, like humans, and there's a natural, strong bond between a mother cow and her calf.
so following their traumatic separation, the mother will bellow and scream for days, wondering where her baby is. 
the answer depends on the gender of the calf. if male, he will probably either be shot and tossed into a bin, or he'll be sold to be raised for veal, which delays his death by just a matter of months. ‚Ä¢ 
calves who are sold for veal will be stuck inside a small pen or a veal crate so they won't develop any muscle tissue so their 'meat' stays tender.
they stay there until they are transported for slaughter at only 18 - 20 weeks old.
‚Ä¢ 
if the calf is female, she will usually be prepared for her own entry into dairy production, where she will face the same cycle of terror that her mother is trapped in: forced impregnation, the theft of her babies and the endless milking. ‚Ä¢ 
once the dairy cows are so worn out that they have produced all the milk they can, they are sent to slaughter, usually at around five years of age; the average natural lifespan of a cow is 18 - 22 years. 
their meat often ends up in low-grade burgers or pet foods.
‚Ä¢ 
help bring an end to an industry that is violent, unnatural and heart breaking on every level üôè.
---------------------------------------------------------------

the answer depends on the gender of the calf. if male, he will probably either be shot and tossed into a bin, or he'll be sold to be raised for veal, which delays his death by just a matter of months. ‚Ä¢ 
calves who are sold for veal will be stuck inside a small pen or a veal crate so they will not develop any muscle tissue so their 'meat' stays tender.
they stay there until they are transpoed for slaughter at only 18 - 20 weeks old.
‚Ä¢ 
if the calf is female, she will usually be prepared for her own entry into dairy production, where she will face the same cycle of terror that her mother is trapped in: forced impregnation, the theft of her babies and the endless milking. ‚Ä¢ 
once the dairy cows are so worn out that they have produced all the milk they can, they are sent to slaughter, usually at around five years of age; the average natural lifespan of a cow is 18 - 22 years. 
their meat often ends up in low-grade burgers or pet foods.
‚Ä¢ 
help bring an end to an industry that is violent, unnatural and hea breaking on every level üôè.

text: seriously, take a hold of your life. when i look back on mine, i realize i never really felt i had control. i was brought up to be a "proverbs 31 woman". which is essentially a quiet, dutiful wife. to always let him make the decisions, to forgive any mistake he may make, specifically to submit to a man. i was taught to sleep with your husband every time he wants it, because not sleeping with him will cause him to go searching for it elsewhere. "men have needs." this.... was definitely brainwashing. i ended up pregnant at 16. i was told he was the provider, and we tried it that way for a while. we got a house 15 miles out of town. i still didn't have a license or access to the outside world.. i decided i wanted to get a job. i wanted control. i was told if i took the job, he'd leave me.  and i was alone. always.the relationship was.... emotionally and mentally abusive. and here i was. fucking him. every time, any way he asked. because that was how i was taught to keep the relationship going. here i was forgiving him every time he called me a dizzy cunt. because a good woman will see her man through anything. fast forward to my leaving him, and being the one ostracized for breaking up our "family". after having a child as a teen, and everything else that happened, i was going through some serious depression. and looking back, i was so fucking desperate for love. desperate for anyone to care about me on a deeper level. i did a lot of self medicating. i did a lot of... floating. not sure of how to get out of the mess i had created. fast forward to my turning point. realizing i had zero respect for the people i was spending time with or the way i allowed them to treat me. and in that sense, zero respect for myself. fast forward to meeting ethan. another turning point. a man who respected me. waited as long as i needed to wait to do the deed. who stood up (respectfully) to our premarital counselor when there was an entire chapter on being a submissive wife. to a man who had a completely different perspective and upbringing than mine, but loved learning about my differences. who taught me about empathy, and being intentional about everything you do. the lo

text:
stepping out of my comfort zone but i feel this needs to be shared. 
for some this may be to real, and for some you may read and move on with out a second thought, for me reading this sends me into a sweating shaking mess as it does for unfortunately many others. 460,000 sexual assaults happen each year in canada, out of a 1000, 33 are reported to police, 29 recorded as a crime, 12 have charges laid, 6 lead to prosecution and 3 are convicted. 997 offenders walk free. i am currently one of the 12 and hanging on everyday to fight for what i believe. 
my hardest struggle? 
i have said it to doctors, lawyers, crown, counsellors, therapists friends and family...the hardest part of this is the lack of support from the people who were there through these times in my life. very few stuck by me and for those people who did i am forever grateful. and well for the rest you should be ashamed, because your friends and daughters deserve more. i will slowly be reaching out to a couple people that i know went through similar times but you all know who you are and i‚Äôm asking you to reach out if you are willing to stand up for not just me but all women, if you are uncomfortable just send me a pm and i‚Äôll give u direct contact info to my lawyer where everything can stay confidential.

on april 16, 2017, in the village of shambhupura in banswara, rajasthan, india, kachru, 21, and monica, 19, got married and were cousins but there family, was not fine with it. the couple were paraded naked, beaten, and sexually assaulted by the whole village of shambhupura and family members including their fathers, brothers and, uncles. the accused have been booked for rioting,¬†wrongful restraint and confinement, wrongly causing hurt, attempted murder, and sexual harassment.
-
-
"the men and children of the village have fled to some other place due to the fear of arrest.
according to the police, on thursday, varaseng resident varanseng resident lord ratna maida, twenty-four-year-old padla resident shankar son lalji, kundelia resident forgotten wife dhulia, resident of shambhupura, gutu son shyama, subhash son hiraji, kangi son kalu, dilip son chetan, ramatu wife kalu and bhusli wife bheema was arrested¬†earlier, nine people including the father of the girl were arrested on wednesday."

text:
what do you want from me?

this song talks about the violence in a relation between two people.they live a constant aggression all the time, until finally the woman says that she can't handle it anymore. this is a realistic song for this complicated world. 
it was written inicially in spanish lenguaje by cristian berrondo and me (an argentinean producer and musician) in argentina. the song was called "qu√© es lo que quieres de mi?", and the last year i've translated it into english for being part of this new album "out of my blue".
this version was recorded in #asturias at @tutuestudios, and the singer @ellecatomusic was singing it a duo with me! 
she is an amazing singer and person, and she has a super career with her own music and she also was the backing vocals of #anastacia and now, she is on tour with #jamiroquail. 
if you wanna listen the complete song, follow me on @spotify & @deezer and with lyrics, on youtube. üòòüòò ------

text:
throughout #february, we will be celebrating #thepowerofwomen in the lead-up to #nationalwomensday. we absolutely support the #metoo movement, and salute the #strongwomen who champion justice and equality. however, we also stand behind some #goodmen too ‚Äì #men with a strong moral code, and the strength of mind to insist that everyone is treated with respect and fairness, regardless of gender.
amidst the publicity about the experiences of women in the public eye, we mustn‚Äôt lose sight of the fact that many men haven‚Äôt had it easy either. take @dylanjonesgq, #editor-in-chief of #gq magazine, who experienced abuse at the hands of his own father, which he had locked away in a quiet corner of his mind until very recently. in common with the women who don‚Äôt let mistreatment take them down, dylan hasn‚Äôt let the negativity of his past shape his future - this interview really says everything we want to say about being a man in the modern world. 
#publicspeaking #motivationalspeaking

text:
i saw this quote last night after a particularly emotional bout of writing. i admit, i did not expect the depth of emotion this latest project had pulled from me. the stories my daughter and i are working on are meant to be light and fun, but something happened with this latest one. it's taken me back to dark days... back to some of the darkest days of my life.

and with all of that in mind, i felt an especially strong response when i saw this quote on the wall of a fellow author i follow.

why is it always the first assumption (when one person compares themself to another) that they must be jealous?

why must jealousy be the obvious answer... the acceptable answer... the expected answer?

why can't we, as fellow human beings, believe that someone can honestly be happy for someone else who has had a great triumph - and still feel sad thinking that they may never achieve their own goals.

that is not jealousy. it is a complex and intricate set of emotions that defines who we are and how we've gotten there.

jealousy is too simple to explain the way i feel when someone does a little happy dance over their great news - and i put on a happy face, while trying desperately to ignore (for the moment) the mountain of despair that will settle again on my shoulders once they've moved on to celebrate with someone else.

perhaps if we could all be a little more understanding of our fellow humans, rather than judging and jumping to conclusions, life just might get a bit easier for all of us.

not to impugn our illustrious former commander-in-chief, but... my own experience has given me a very different perspective on this particular quote: "comparison is nothing more than the lie the bullies of the world desperately need us to believe." - jc morrows (a direct quote from our wip)

when a man wear nice clothes we do not assume he wants to get the sexual attention of female bystanders they don't even know. 
they have the right to dress for themselves.
same for women.

text:
üíÅ‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è+ üíÅ‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è
.
de gestampte meisjes (ymke van hoof, esm√©e van liera and thenera van der pluijm) think it's about time to put men back on a pedestal. since women think they're capable of everything and don't need male assistance, the classic role division has evaporated. .
the result: many insecure men. if #metoo is the order of the day, and you have to be scared of everything you say and do, then walking on egg shells is all there's left to do as a man.
.
but, de gestampte meisjes do need men. in their performance 'ballen; ballen 2.0' they explore what men really want, what women want from men, and what they want from each other. .
in a humorous and completely unabashed way, the three ladies play with stereotypes of female dependency, docility and compliance.
.

text:
some folks like hugs, some dont. and that's ok. don't make it weird, ask first, and respect the answer :) whether you're going in for a hug, taking a picture, or getting under the covers with someone, consent is mandatory.

artwork by @introvertdoodles

image description: three green scroll banners on a white background read "some folks like hugs", "some folks don't", "and that's okay". illustrated animals are all over the image. a brown snake says "tighter pleassse". a yellow pufferfish says "you're in my bubble". a possum playing dead says "i'm dead, go away". a green turtle says "retreat!". a grey porcupine says "don't even try it". a pink and blue octopus says "free hugs! limit 8 per person". a brown koala bear says "let's hang out and cuddle". in the bottom right-hand corner is the tag for @introvertdoodles

text:
while serving in the u.s. üá∫üá∏ navy, jonathan morrow knew he wanted to advance his career‚Äîwhether he stayed in the military or not. he decided an mba would be the best way to do so. due to his undergrad coming from cu boulder, he chose cu denver to pursue his professional mba. with the option of completing the program fully online, he knew that he could complete the work regardless of where the navy sent him. 
upon exiting the military, the transition into veteran life and the stresses of starting a new job hit morrow hard. however, he was able to find a job in an engineering role where he was quickly promoted twice within 14 months. morrow attributes this to his undergraduate and navy experience, along with the knowledge he‚Äôs gained in the professional mba program. 
morrow is inspired by diversity and inclusion, especially among women. he served with a young lady who was among one of the first enlisted ladies to serve on submarines. morrow mentored her for years to come and she was eventually promoted to chief petty officer‚Äîone of the most difficult promotions to get. this was his first foray into mentoring.

along with mentoring women in the navy, he applies his education to mentoring women in engineering. he works tirelessly to achieve equal treatment and pay among women. 
morrow is thankful his coursework in the mba program helped him to understand ethical concepts, business sustainability, and how to deal with people directly. as he continues to advance his career, he looks forward to making even bigger moves in the engineering industry and helping the women around him.

text:
ochre ribbon week occurs annually between 12th - 19th february. the ochre ribbon campaign is an initiative supported by the national family violence prevention legal services forum and its member organisations across australia. the ochre ribbon campaign raises awareness of the devastating impacts of family violence in aboriginal and torres strait islander communities and calls for action to end the violence against aboriginal and torres strait islander people ‚Äì especially our women and children. 
violence against aboriginal and torres strait islander women devastates communities and destroys families. in comparison with other women, aboriginal and torres strait islander women are 32 times more likely to be hospitalised from family violence and 10 times more likely to be killed as a result of violent assault. 
you can raise awareness of this national crisis and show your support for the work of the national forum by sharing these infographics on social media. text:
food for thought - a beautiful and tragic poem by @atholwilliams . thanks @lesleydw  for sharing... #metoo #metoomovement 
the black poetess says
the virus of privilege thrives even among
those
who carry the #metoo hashtag on their 
thighs.
where some tell their stories from cocoons
of serviced bedroom suites, most lie 
awake
at night in jaw-clenched silence, in tiny 
rooms
decorated with large reminders. these 
women
continue to sleep there, packed in tight
with their demons, for without them, who
will guard the door, who will pay the bills?

text:
#leadership
.
whether you're an early-stage entrepreneur or an accomplished leader, know that in the age of social media, who you choose to follow means something.
.
it says a lot about who you are. it says a lot about your values. it says a lot about who you honor with your time and attention.
.
i typically don't call out people on social, but, this frightened me.
.
i listened to @evancarmichael on the @altucher podcast. i liked what i heard. he seemed authentic and truly interested in elevating #success (his motto: #believe)..¬†i started following him on insta. it appears that his multi-million dollar business is curating leader's top 10 rules for success.
.
today, @evancarmichael glorified mike tyson with tyson's 10 rules. tyson, a man convicted of raping an 18-year-old. a man who became famous for ripping off the ear of an opponent. a man who squandered his wealth and filed for bankruptcy. a man who's headline today is "mike tyson sighted smoking a foot long joint." .
when social influencers like @evancarmichael glorify men like tyson, a few things are happening. 1) he assumes you won't do your research on the person he puts forth as successful (in other words, that you're stupid), 2) he might be assuming that tyson's success in the ring excludes all his other awful characteristics #toxicmasculinity, 3) he is not at all thoughtful or careful about who he uses his following to promote, preferring likes and comments to social value.
.
you are making a statement about your values, your integrity, and your time when you give your attention to people. treat it carefully and make sure your social presence aligns with who you are, your standards. and, now, i will go and unfollow @evancarmichael and maybe even @altucher. 
#leadership #quality #success #values #socialresponsibility #choice #voice #metoo

text:
release the pain behind your smile ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
at some stage in our life, we have all had to force a smile and pretend to be ok - when all we really wanted to do was hide. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
i spent 15 years forcing a smile and pretending my life was perfect when i was really suffering. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
i was raped when i was 15. i didn‚Äôt tell anyone for 8 months and tried to end my life. i couldn‚Äôt confide in my friends because ‚Äúas if you wouldn‚Äôt be able to fight them off and run away‚Äù. so i taught myself to move on - to ‚Äúblock‚Äù the pain.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
unfortunately that wasn‚Äôt the only ‚Äúbad‚Äù thing that happened to me (domestic violence, stalking, bullying etc)... but it was the worst. i also developed destructive habits and made mistakes because life was easier when i was in pain. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
i spent the next 15 years being the fun loving extravert most of the time - and every 6 months spend 2 weeks in a deep depression. that was my normal. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
only after i hit rock bottom again at the age of 30 did i decide to do something. i said ‚Äúfuck this‚Äù my life doesn‚Äôt have to be like this. i worked on myself - i got a coach and a psych and i worked my arse off. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
in doing this - i realized that the reason all of this happened to me, was so i could help you overcome the adversity in your life. the person that you can talk to, the person that understands and tells you it‚Äôs not your fault, the person that tells you that you can be whoever and whatever you want to be!!‚†Ä
‚†Ä
it saddens me to know that these horrible things are far too common. that other people have been victims as well. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
my past is no longer a hidden dark secret. they are the scars that forms my imperfectly perfect life. they‚Äôre part of who i am. i can finally talk about it - release it from the hold it had on me. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
i‚Äôm here to tell you that you can overcome the obstacle that‚Äôs getting in your way. you can be yourself, you can say what you want and not care about what other people think. you can love the person who you are. you can be happy and reach for any goal you desire. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
i‚Äôm here to empower and encourage you to live the life you‚Äôve always wanted... but might have been too scared to ask for. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
üíôüòò

text:
i used to believe that i just wasn't the type of woman to have close girlfriends.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
my career started off in a male dominated industry where i was just one of a few women among 50+ men in the office.

it was easier to just be 'one of the guys' to get by.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
it was easier to believe the garbage we've been fed that women are catty and competitive and snarky.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
it was easier to ignore the sexist comments... or the boob staring... or conversations about how plans to troll bars and have one-night stands while on the road for work.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
it was easier until it wasn't.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
it was easier until that shit was directed at me.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
it was easier until i stopped feeling safe at work.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
that's when it really hit me that no matter how far women have come in the workplace, toxic masculinity was fighting us every step of the way.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
and that toxic masculinity is alive and well in the entrepreneurial community too.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
over the last couple of years, i've heard so many stories of men who happily sell their programs to women, but don't stand up and fight for women in the wake of #metoo and pussy grabbing.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
stories of conferences dominated by men, where there is not a single woman (much less a woman of color) speaking and when asked why, they say there just aren't any women experts.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
stories of men hosting masterminds and events where they would openly sexually harass the very women who had just paid tens of thousands of dollars to be there.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
and at the same time - despite knowing this - many women feel like they can't get ahead unless they get into those rooms, into those circles, next to those influencers.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
i'm over it.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
when i knew i wanted a coach and a mastermind this year, i knew i wanted to invest in women.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
i hire women on my team. i buy from women owned businesses. i research the software companies we use to see if they have women in leadership or are women founded.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
it's time for us to create our own rooms, our own circles of influence, and our own conferences.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
because behind every great woman, are great women.
name: Biz Strategist for Women CEOs

text: do you ever struggle to feel at peace with exactly who and what you are? to really honour yourself? to be true to yourself? anais goes on to say ‚Äúto take pride in my thoughts, my appearance, my talents, my flaws and to stop this incessant worrying that i can‚Äôt be loved as i am‚Äù. i feel like this mission has been my life‚Äôs journey.  to focus on my talents as well as my flaws.  to learn gently, slowly, to stop all the ways i still subtly strive to change myself from a place of not believing i can be loved as i am.  i am passionate about personal growth, yet when it comes from a place of ‚Äòi am not enough as i am‚Äô, of not accepting myself, it really is just another form of self-criticism or self-abuse. i used to think ‚Äòtaking pride in my appearance‚Äô meant looking good, but i really get now that taking pride in my appearance, as i am, is what it is all about. loving my uniqueness and physical ‚Äòimperfections‚Äô ‚Äì oh if only our culture supported that. i needed to come face to face with my flaws but not from a place of harsh self-criticism, instead from a place of curiosity, understanding and self-compassion. to understand why i think the way i think, why i behave the way i behave.  to meet all those parts of me i push away or try to ignore, especially those parts of me that i feel scared or ashamed of. i have also learnt to see and believe in my talents and strengths. now that has been challenging! to do that fully, means i need to face all the fears that come with that. allowing my creativity to flow has been challenging. believing in myself has been challenging. it‚Äôs been hard to get clear on my talents and strengths, to what is really important to me and even harder to start living a life true to myself. no easy feat! scary! and yet such a deeply satisfying way to live my life. i found i needed a path to learn how to know myself, care for myself and be myself and it gives me such joy to watch hundreds of women go through our online program to learn just that. our vision at is to empower 1 million women to do this through our online program and to really live true to that vision we have decided to drop the price from usd $197 to aud $47. it means giving away...

text:
astrology and blackface

if you remember during the #metoo movement jupiter was transiting through scorpio‚ôè. how that works is that scorpio‚ôè rules the hidden, secrets, oppression,  and sex while jupiter in astrology is the "truth seeker". .
.

so, yes secrets about sex that were deeply hidden surfaced to the spotlight.  with all the recent blackface revelations from the governor of virginia, to gucci and their sweaters, katie perry and her shoes, etc. .
.  i had to think of how this is indicated in the heavens.  i figured it out.  jupiter entered sagittarius‚ôê this past november which is the sign it rules.  sagittarius‚ôê rules justice and... philosophy.  these old pics of blackface is somehow linked to these individual's philosophical ideas about race.
.
.  does it mean their racist?  not always.  but it sure does make people wonder.  since jupiter is the law, there is a sense of justice for those who participated in the acts of blackface. .
.

so if you are out there and took some questionable pics having to do with blackface, be aware that you could be served some type of justice behind it.  even  people of color are catching heat for it.  should be interesting. .
.

text:
thank you, as always, @ladygaga for standing up and saying what needed to be said about mental health. .
.
the topic of being present for others who are suffering is a topic i‚Äôve thought about, wrote about, and talked about for years. beaten down by a society that wants us to brush off trauma, abuse, and emotional suffering ‚Äî i searched for something or someone to show me this way of existing and relating was as toxic as i felt it was. .
.
sure enough, i discovered the term ‚Äúspiritual bypassing‚Äù several years ago and it explained what i couldn‚Äôt. from wikipedia, spiritual bypassing is described as ‚Äútendency to use spiritual ideas and practices to sidestep or avoid facing unresolved emotional issues, psychological wounds, and unfinished developmental tasks.‚Äù
.
.
sound familiar? you go to someone with a problem/loss/heartbreak, and they tell you not to feel sad, or to cheer up, or that better days are ahead. this person may even provide you with an inspirational quote or a scripture. veiled in spirituality or positivity, what this person just did is sidestep the suffering of the person in front of them. perhaps you have done this. it is important to be compassionate with ourselves even if we discover we participate in spiritual bypassing. .
.
to sit with the pain of another takes an unlearning of the habit to bypass it. it also takes strong boundaries and vulnerability. while i am advocating more of us practice being present with our own pain and that of others, we are not required to be there for anyone and everyone who asks us to. and definitely not when we aren‚Äôt well enough to do so. we must use the oxygen mask on ourselves first before helping others to breathe. but we can, help them breathe, and it is in our nature to do this for each other. .
#traumaqueen #traumaqueenwellness #ladygaga #spiritualbypassing #compassion #mentalhealth #selfcompassion #bekindtoothers #bekindtoyou #survivor #dvsurvivor #metoo #timesup #feminista #intersectionalfeminism #invisiblescars #selflove #activelistening #loveoneanother #humannature

.

text: i consider myself a lifelong learner. i absolutely love leadership and love learning. developing into the person you want to become doesn't just happen. you have to be intentional. the truth is, i'm always seeking.  i realize there are so many brilliant people out there and i just want a little piece of what they have to offer. i hope one day after going through this experience, i'll be able to share a little priece of me through a book that will help others. i feel like i'm navigating through unchartered waters at times. as my friend said, "when you lead something controversial it's a lonely place." it doesn't have to be and i hope to change that, but for today i'll snuggle my baby, take care of my family and pick up a good book. #bookclub #realwomen #brave #hope #womenleaders #beautyforashes #godsgirl #leadershiptraining #cslewis #brenebrown #erwinmcmanus

text:
sorry for the blurry picture. i'm seriously so happy whatever was hovering over me is dissipating. üòä progress is being made mentally and physically. someone told me they couldnt give me what i need and deserve, and i realized i wasnt doing that for myself. i stopped doing that. grief, my health, and stress really got me down. i struggled with #sadd hard and am still battling it as are many others. watching you all do and go go go makes me believe in my ability to get back to it and to succeed. you all on your own ways helped me realize i stopped loving me, that i had not a clue what i wanted, needed, or where i'm going. still a little lost on that last one. the last 2 years have been one grief and stressful event after another. i want to heal and have a moment to take advantage of and appreciate. so i am!! i'm actually looking forward to the more challenging workouts that i use to do. i just got lost in the fog for a bit. it happens, and i know may happen again. 
i forget how much this helps me too often and too easily. gosh ya'll, i've had less muscle cramping, less #raynauds and #erythromelalgia flare ups. i can say i start to get scared when i feel the heat and pain occuring during a work out. i just try to watch it and be mindful that this is a good sweat and pain. that it leads to less bad ones. sometimes i still hear my exhusband, dad, and stepmom and it gets to me. i'm also self destructive often due to abandonment issues and #ptsd, and through therapy have accepted i continue abusing myself because i dont know/remember another life. this is helping clear my mind, its helping me be less self destructive, its helping me have healthy energy and thoughts, its helping me believe in my ability to win the current fight i'm in for my own justice. i'm tired, but i'm not ready to give up. i will look back and smile. now is my time! 
#domesticviolencerecovery #metoo #workitout #sweatitout #spoonie #yoga #pilates #lifetransformation #mentalhealth #physicalhealth #recovery #blogger #blog #divorcedlife #divorcerecovery #abuserecovery #survivor #fighter #fibromyalgia #fibrowarrior #matlife #selfcare #queer #tomboi #tomboy #lgbtq

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since day one.

steve bannon left the wh august 2017 and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? 'j-c' church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt, with the goonsquad known as gop, has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagate‚Ñ¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are useless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is no way that gop isn't aware of this - after all, cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got as cambridge analytica. pedofiles - i bet - but the way things are bundled sure makes goebbels shiver.

trump plays along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still - the republicans willingly piggybacked this before the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since day one.

steve bannon left the wh august 2017 and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? 'j-c' church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt, with the goonsquad known as gop, has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagate‚Ñ¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are useless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is no way that gop isn't aware of this - after all, cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got as cambridge analytica. pedofiles - i bet - but the way things are bundled sure makes goebbels shiver.

trump plays along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still - the republicans willingly piggybacked this before the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
women's issues are men's issues. so many problems facing women today exist because of how our society handles and teaches masculinity.
"toxic masculinity" is a popular term heard today, and it affects both men and women. addressing this negative behavior that our society so commonly accepts as normal is the first major step in overcoming toxic masculinity and freeing both men and women to live more equitably.

text:
a group of young french media executives was condemned monday for running a macho 'boys' club' that harassed female colleagues online.

their closed¬†facebook¬†group 'league of lol' - made up mostly of men in their thirties - ridiculed women journalists for years, sometimes using pornographic memes to attack them.
women seen as feminist were the group's favourite targets.
the founder of the group, journalist vincent glad, was suspended monday by left-wing daily liberation after an investigation by the newspaper's own fact-checking unit exposed its existence.

founder of the group, journalist vincent glad, was suspended monday by left-wing daily liberation
the revelations also led to the suspension of the newspaper's online editor alexandre hervaud and his opposite number at france's trendiest music and culture magazine, les inrockuptibles, david doucet.
the affair is being dubbed the 'french media's #metoo', with liberation referring to the group as a 'boys' club' which bullied women online and cracked off-colour jokes about rape culture

an investigation by the newspaper's own fact-checking unit exposed its existence
victims of the group recounted how the attacks and pranks had pushed one woman to quit journalism and left another suicidal.
#leagueoflol targeted science presenter florence porcel, seeking to humiliate her by getting group members to pose as the producers of a prestigious television programme offering her a job, then posted the recording of the fake interview online.
other women had their heads grafted onto pornographic images.
set up in 2009, the league of lol also had members in public relations, graphic design, and media eduction. it had been much less active in recent years.
the head of a porn culture website stepped down monday and suspended his le tag parfait (the perfect tag) blog, apologising for his part in the activities of the group that gets its name from the acronym for 'laugh out loud'. stephen des aulnois admitted the league of lol was guilty of 'repeated online harassment. i apologise to all those i hurt and harassed... i am also guilty of silence and inaction during all those years when i knew.' #laliguedulol #slutshaming
@vscyberh

text:
social fam!! bear with me on this post. if you don‚Äôt have the time or interest to read it all, know that the point is that you are enough!! üíØüî• i look at this picture and it reminds me of a time when i would never smile in a photo. a time when i could find so many things wrong with me, my appearance, or who i was. after being molested when i was about 5/6 years old, i struggled with a lot of things, mainly insecurities. if someone would‚Äôve told me then that at 32 years old, i would be pursuing a professional acting career, i would‚Äôve believed they were making fun of me. i share this with you because it took me 28+ years to get to the place i‚Äôm at now and just maybe, my story can help speed up that process for someone else. i am still learning who i am, but i‚Äôm loving who i am and am embracing the freedom to be me. there‚Äôs so much more i could say but if you‚Äôve read this far, i don‚Äôt want to abuse your attention lol. so i‚Äôll end it by saying to anyone who‚Äôll receive this, know that you are enough!! you‚Äôre not what people call you, only what you answer to. don‚Äôt be afraid to embrace who you are because at the end of the day, even if it‚Äôs just you and god who loves you for you...it‚Äôs already more than enough! finally, the sky is not the limit, it‚Äôs only the beginning...so #dreambig!! üôåüèæüíö‚úäüèæ #ismilemorenow #thankyoulord #livelaughlove #lovemore #loveyourself #iamenough #freedom #metoo #enjoyingmyprocess #actor #producer #director #motivationalspeaker #leadingman #nyc #atl #hollywood #futureoscarwinner #iamtj

‚Å£
i was diagnosed with depression, ptsd & anxiety back in 2015 after i was sexually assaulted. my soul was drowning in a life i had never imagined for myself. i was doing everything i could to make it from day to day and sometimes even minute to minute. ‚è∞ ‚Å£
‚Å£
my coping skills? life threatening. i would take more than the prescribed amount of xanax and swallow them down with enough rum to make myself black out.  i cut my forearms until i ran out of room and was forced to switch to my thighs and hips. i woke up in the icu in several occasions between december ‚Äò15 and september ‚Äò16. i never tried to intentionally kill myself, but i knew if that happened i was at peace with it. my body was taken advantage of. it was no longer my own. my rapist left my body filthy, disgusting, and unclean. ‚Å£
‚Å£
it‚Äôs february 2019. i still suffer from depression, ptsd, and anxiety. what‚Äôs different now? my coping skills.üíï i have learned healthy ways to cope that do not put my life on the line. i‚Äôve taken back my body, because i freaking can. i have that power now. i am no longer ‚ùå the filthy, disgusting and unclean corpse my rapist had once made me into. ‚Å£
‚Å£
when i say i workout for my mental, it‚Äôs because i do. my life depends on it.üíì‚Å£
‚Å£

text:
tomorrow i will be releasing into the wild six+ years of my blood, sweat, and tears crammed into a 2-hour-ish online course.  i was talking to someone today about how much went into this.  it's not, like, a curriculum i sat down and created one day.  it's years of poring full-time over the problem that "our rights in birth are virtually disregarded without recourse all over the country" (and the world) with wonderful advocates and dedicated lawyers and hurt, brave, determined survivors.  it's soul-crushing secondary trauma from supporting birth workers and parents in horrific, unjust situations.  it's staying up all night many nights emailing reporters to "please report on the maternity care crisis" (good news: they are now :) ), because the law, the state, and the hospital system have no answers for us when we've been violated in birth.  worse, they re-victimize us.
.
all that to say, i am so ready to push this particular project out the door and into the world.  i want to see every birth worker armed with the knowledge and confidence that the birthing person is the legal authority in birth.  period.
.
know your rights: legal and human rights in childbirth for birth professionals and advocates... because of the density of this topic and how it changes and develops, i decided that the course alone wouldn't cut it.  so i added to the course a private group and regular q&as with me so we can build this base together.  a little birth rights army :)
.
if everyone understood the rights of birthing people, we could flip maternity care on its head tomorrow.  why not start... tomorrow?
.
üéâüéâ update: class is open! get in now at the introductory price: www.birthmonopoly.com/know-your-rights-course
.

text:
the femenine energy is something that has intrigue me lately. 
and i am a woman, i would imagine that by being one i should have known more about it.  but "should's" and "must's" are something i been keeping on check lately as i move into my 30's. i have learned that the femenine energy is both in females and males and has nothing to do with gender. what i have understood so far is that the femenine energy, among other beautiful things, has to do with the ability to have, express and be ok with having feelings. in the femenine energy field, emotions are seen as an asset and not as a  weakness. 
we are beginning to understand how our brain developed thru hundreds of thousands of years and how it begun with emotions as a way to keep the species safe. thought came later in evolution. from this point of view, emotions are a call  to action. to move towards safety, to run away from the saber-toothed tiger. 
the practice, at least for me, is to be ok with having emotions, understanding that is part of who i am as a human and not because i am a woman. allowing emotions to be there, hold their space, and then practice even more to be able to use them as a way to move, to act on the best way. i think, aristotle puts on a very simple and clear manner, and i am paraphrasing: anybody can get upset, that is very easy. but to get upset with the right person, with the correct amount of energy, at the right moment, with an honest  purpose and with a proper manner, that, certainly, is not that easy. 
and so the journey continues. 
#femenine #femenineenergy #trust #healing #transformation #aunthenticity #journey #metoo

text:
here they are again, the thoughts that i detest. the ones i suppress so far down my subconscious. they bubble back up into my brain and remind me of something unpleasant. i try and fight them, but they‚Äôre stubborn. images of your hands reaching for me when i was asleep, spin around in my head, with added flashes of your hungry eyes, as you preyed on me, without guilt. i stayed, because i was afraid, not because i wanted to. the word ‚Äúlove‚Äù spilled from your lips like i meant everything to you, but it meant nothing to me. your eyes claimed my body and your greed claimed my innocence. you told me how beautifully made i was. stitched together with the perfect amount of what you‚Äôd want to destroy. love was just something you used to make sense of what you did. i was just a mere pawn, in your grand scheme of self pleasure. -kavya baburaj .
.

you grabbed my leg because ‚Äúboys will be boys.‚Äù
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
you watched me squirm and try to pull away and you smiled because ‚Äúboys will be boys.‚Äù
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
you laughed with your high school friends at my uncomfortableness while onlookers on the train did nothing because ‚Äúboys will be boys.‚Äù
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
you had no idea what i‚Äôve been through, what bruises were once right where your hand was sitting.

you had no idea that the last time a guy put his unwanted hand on me, it lead to the worst day of my life.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
what you thought was ‚Äúboys being boys‚Äù was so much more to me.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
can we please, p l e a s e  stop throwing that phrase around as a catch-all and start holding people accountable for their actions?  because i am sick of people getting away with sexual assault and my heart is broken for those who can‚Äôt get justice because ‚Äúboys will be boys‚Äù.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
today i‚Äôm smiling with a little extra help from god‚Äôs promise - ‚Äúin this world you will have trouble.  but take heart! i have overcome the world.‚Äù

as white people, we cannot truly understand the experience of people of color. however, our goal is to try to help to dismantle the oppressive system from which we benefit in order to bring about equity. we decided to research and make a list detailing how we, as white people, can be allies to poc. 
stand up against racist actions, statements, and jokes ‚Üí you‚Äôd think this is simply a given, it‚Äôs not. do not be complicit in racism. stumble upon a racist meme? report it. see blackface? call them out. people that you know are not black using the n-word? shut that down. 
do not take leadership away from poc ‚Üí for example, in the blm white people started to get frustrated that they were not being given key roles in organizing, planning, etc. why? the whole point is to empower and protect black people, they should not be lead by white people who cannot truly understand what they‚Äôve been through. if you want to support poc, do not take away their voice. 
recognize that while you may feel upset or hurt as well, the conversation is not about you. take actions to keep the conversation on track and not focused on white people issues. 
amplify the voices of poc, do not speak over them.
be educated. we must learn of our absolutely horrific past of oppression in which we tortured, enslaved, and murder poc. do not gloss over our past. (posts about white oppression in history coming soon)
become aware of your implicit biases. you may not realize you have them, but we all do.
 if it‚Äôs not explicit already, no one under any circumstance, unless you are a black person, should use the n-word

please dm or comment additions to this list so that we can improve upon it!

.
until the #metoo movement started, i don‚Äôt know that i fully realized how easy i have had it in life. when i started hearing friends, family, colleagues, and acquaintances all come out and tell their stories of ‚Äòthat time,‚Äô i was stunned. i‚Äôm no dummy, i know this kind of thing happens, but i had no idea how pervasive the issue was (and is). i had no idea that it was happening to person after person that i know. sometimes right in front of my eyes. üòî
.
love takes work. people argue, disagree, fight, and bicker. but true love does not truly hurt. it does not attack, control, manipulate. though i have never fallen prey to any #metoo situations, i have been in some pretty bad relationships. men who sought to control my destiny (good luck). men who cut me off from friends. men who told me i was dumb (no need to study for that exam, let‚Äôs go out). men who used me for money. men who tried to cut me off from my family. men who made me feel unworthy, undeserving, and sad. üôáüèª‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è
.
i am so blessed that i grew a pair of ovaries and left those d-bags. to all the women on this page, especially the young women: you matter. you will be believed when you speak up. you do not have to stay with that jerk because you worry you‚Äôll never find another. if your partner treats you like crap, if they hurt you psychologically, physically, financially, or emotionally...girl, he‚Äôs just not that into you and tell him boy, bye. üôãüèª‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è
.
trust me. you‚Äôre worth it. üòò
.
what‚Äôs been your best lesson in love?
.

(the poem is gendered. i am aware that the reality is a lot more nuanced and that rape victims include men and a lot of non-cisnormative people. i wrote this specifically on the perspective of mexico, where the femicide epidemic is a national emergency, and crimes related to trans- and homophobia are of a different nature and have different executions. if you wanna come at me √† la ‚Äúall lives matter‚Äù, though, i‚Äôll still have that conversation with you). .
.
i‚Äôve been given hours upon hours of advice to avoid getting raped. only recently have people around me started wondering why we never taught men not to rape. .
.
so i was thinking about how my approach to everything since i realized that the world is fucked is to be really introspective and to be the best version of myself and avoid confrontation with people and maybe if everybody likes me enough then life‚Äôs fuckery will just go around me. .
.
but tbh i‚Äôm really tired of only having an opinion on important issues around my friends just because i‚Äôm scared of getting into arguments on stuff that i care about. .
.
so yes excuse me while i start speaking about stuff other than what goes on in my very loud internal universe, because i may be the smiliest soul you‚Äôve ever met but i still really wanna punch a wall half of the time. .
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
this is a strange little space, wouldn‚Äôt you say?

when i first jumped onto @instagram i never imagined what this space would become; posting here terrified me. truly, the idea of sharing photos or saying a thing about anything was paralyzing. my dear friend, @trevlee, a deep well of patience + unending encouragement coaxed me out of my shell + that‚Äôs where this journey began.

over the years, this space has been a number of things.

it has been a space to practice opening up, a place of community + a place to realize i‚Äôm not alone. especially during those times when an astounding number of women shared their stories of harassment + sexual trauma; any courage i‚Äôve found to begin opening up w. those closest to me has been built piece by piece by those stories. #metoo #ibelieveher

it has been an outlet of accountability to process the searching for my brother in the philippines during #theheritageproject. to my surprise, people started showing up, sharing their stories + cheering from the sidelines of the long emotional road i was walking. it reminded me of when marathon runners reach that point of exhaustion, bodies beat + then unexpectedly strangers begin cheering, encouraging + running alongside them (i cry every time i witness this).
.
this has been a space to process losing a friend unexpectedly to suicide.

a space of travel, sharing stories of folks i‚Äôve met along the way + work i‚Äôm proud of.

a space to peek in on old friends to see what they‚Äôre eating for dinner + make new friends + peek in on them to see what they‚Äôre eating for dinner.

a space to fumble my way into + through motherhood + now a space i spam w. photos of a tiny human that has expanded my understanding of love.

thank you for coming up into my head with me + for those occasional cheers of encouragement from the sidelines. thank you for sharing your thoughts, advice + stories with me. truly. i‚Äôm so grateful that you‚Äôd share a piece of you with me.

while what i post has evolved greatly, my intention in occupying this tiny corner of this strange space is to continue the practice of opening up + to strive to engage in meaningful conversation. i hope you feel so inclined to do the same.

text:
*** highlight alert ***
meet jayce @jaycebaron 
jayce baron sadler is a published author, social entrepreneur, influencer, and advocate for the lgbtq+ millennial. executive director of the nationally recognized kiss & tell networks, he has an organic desire to bring a conscious conversation to the community through live events, media, and digital platforms. he is a contributing writer for several publications including hiv equal and message magazine and has been the face of campaigns with the cdc, hornet, and jack'd. in 2016, jayce was invited to the capital to continue to bring awareness to sexual assault, specifically with men, and was part of passing bill sb816 with assemblymember mike gipson and attorney gloria alred revoking the statute of limitation on rape in the state of california. since then, huge national movements such as #metoo, the bill cosby case, and several unresolved rape cases have made their way to court. jayce is currently shopping his family dramedy pilot "literally annoyed" and you can catch him every friday on the west coast black spicy podcast kiss & tell radio alongside pop culture journalist @sharsaysso 
jayce is continuing to partner with several businesses and organizations to guide conscious conversations. he is the lead of developing the kadeem hardison scholarship fund helping young black students get excel in higher education. jayce has just appointed the role of youth advocacy director for idp success in los angeles.
favorite quote: "you're only given a certain amount of energy per lifetime... use it wisely." jayce, we commented and salute you for your work in literacy, advocacy, media and education. we are honored to celebrate our kings of tomorrow, today. #blackmeninmedia #blackhistorymonth #futureblackhistory #ifyoudontknownowyouknow #blackkings

text:
each year, as far back as i can remember, i‚Äôve celebrated that cliche but welcome ‚Äúfresh start‚Äù at the new year. ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
this year was different‚Äî the spell of my typical new year‚Äôs optimism was cast off by a sadness that‚Äôd laid deeper roots than i‚Äôd previously been willing or able to identify. so, i listened to my pain and spent the past month (plus) caring for myself. ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
my attention alchemized my pain into a newfound power with which i feel like ‚Äúmy new year‚Äù can now begin. in this new year, i‚Äôm motivated to share what‚Äôs caused me so much grief with the hope that sharing may help others. ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
the thing is, nearly 3 years ago i was sexually assaulted while on a date. ptsd followed and intensified once i filed police reports and lawsuits (now closed). as i‚Äôve healed i‚Äôve struggled with how to or if i even should share this crime and its effects. what would be the value? ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
my story (unfortunately) isn‚Äôt uncommon and while sexual assault and trauma are dark and difficult topics they‚Äôre also very real. thankfully in this post ‚Äúme too‚Äù era there‚Äôs a lot more support readily available and there‚Äôs less stigma towards the victims. however i know there are so many who‚Äôve suffered the same and i believe adding my voice will only help progress the collective healing. ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
additionally, my trauma and healing process has been so influential in my life that i can‚Äôt imagine not fully integrating what i‚Äôve been through and learned into my mission as a teacher, healer, coach and mentor. ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
so, in the coming weeks, i‚Äôll share more about my experience with the aim to help empower and advocate for sexual assault victims and those suffering from ptsd.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
here‚Äôs to the new year and all the goodness that comes with living in vulnerability, authenticity, and service. and thank you *so* much to my friends, family, and therapist who are the reasons i‚Äôve been able to find the courage to heal and rediscover purpose in my life + work again. ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
need support now? dm me or check out @rainn & @plannedparenthood
